35. Aedilitatem. The aediles had the general charge of the public build- ings, and among them of the temples. Along with these they had the duty of superintending the festivals of the god5‚ aud the games (ludi) which were performed in their honour. In the later period of the republic the aediles, in order to make themselves popular, with a view to gaining afterwards the higher offices, incurred enormous expenses in making these as splendid as they could, and adding various attractions to them. Cicero here alludes to one way in which they did this, by borrowing works of art to adorn the forum or other places where the celebrations were held. See also Pt. 1. Sect. a. 26. 2, and the note on Letter to Quintus, l. 228.
